\end_inset

.
 The Coefficient of Determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coefficient of determination
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 has a minimum of 0 and a maximum of 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 mostly about 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how big
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the error variance is compared to the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Proportion of Variance Explained
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some people write that the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 represents the proportion of variance in y explained by x.
 Where do they get that?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Total Sum of Squares: 
\begin_inset Formula $TSS=\sum(y_{i}-\bar{y})^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Error Sum of Squares: 
\begin_inset Formula $ESS=\sum(y_{i}-\hat{y}_{i})^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regression Sum of Squares
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $RSS=TSS-ESS$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $RSS=\sum(\hat{y}_{i}-\bar{y}_{i})^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout BeginFrame
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Proportion of Variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

(cont)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Notice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TSS=RSS+ESS
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Divide all terms by 
\begin_inset Formula $TSS$
\end_inset

 and we see that the two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proportions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of variance add up to one
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\frac{RSS}{TSS}+\frac{ESS}{TSS}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That's
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1=part\, accounted\, for\, by\, regression+part\, accounted\, for\, by\, error
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Proportion of Variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

(cont)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coefficient of determination
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{2}=\frac{RSS}{TSS}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
which is the same as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\frac{ESS}{TSS}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Put that in words: 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the proportion of variance left over after we take out the part contributed
 by random error term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Calculate the 'anova' table for a regression model, you'll see for yourself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
How Important is 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Experienced statisticians may have rules of thumb about 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 should be bigger than 0.2 before a model is worth reporting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For various reasons (next slides), I think that's silly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sometimes practitioners think a low 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a general warning sign that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

something is wrong.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That's also mistaken: it might be there's not powerful predictive relationship
 to be found.
 We shouldn't torture the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 is partly dependent on the error term's variance, and we will see later
 that big variance -> wide confidence intervals.
 I often do wish error variance were smaller.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout BeginFrame
Don't Over-Emphasize 
